    "teacherReflection": "1. During the Quick Recall Grid, which bond types or substances did the majority of students struggle to recall independently — and does this pattern suggest a gap in earlier lessons (e.g., Lesson 5's hydrogen bonds and Van der Waals forces) that needs to be revisited before or during Lesson 8's modelling project?\n2. During the Substance Evidence Card rotation, were students able to accurately draw Lewis/structural diagrams (especially graphite's layered structure and diamond's tetrahedral network) from memory, or did most groups rely heavily on the ARES animation — and what does this tell me about the depth of structural understanding versus surface recall?\n3. In the Spotlight Share presentations, did students use causal language (e.g., 'because the metallic bond allows electron sea movement, aluminium conducts electricity AND can be beaten into shape') or did they default to listing facts — and which groups demonstrated the strongest evidence-to-explanation reasoning?\n4. When reviewing the DQB, which questions remained in the 'STILL WONDERING' column — and are these conceptual gaps (e.g., why water's hydrogen bonds make it a good solvent) or questions about applications (e.g., industrial uses of graphite in Kenya) that the Lesson 8 project can specifically address?\n5. Did the cumulative model revision and Headline Statement task reveal whether students can articulate the full explanatory chain (bond type → structure → property → Kenyan use) independently and in their own words — or are students still writing the chain as disconnected steps rather than as a unified causal explanation?",
    "summaryTablePrompt": {
      "observed": "Students observed that all six bond types learned across Lessons 1–6 produce distinctly different structures, and that these structural differences — the ionic lattice in NaCl, the layered hexagonal sheets in graphite, the rigid tetrahedral network in diamond, the metallic electron sea in aluminium, the polar covalent bonds in water — directly determine the measurable physical properties each substance displays.",
      "learned": "Bond type determines structure; structure determines physical properties (melting point, solubility, conductivity, hardness); and physical properties determine real-world uses. NaCl's ionic lattice makes it soluble and its solution conductive — ideal for food preservation and electrolytes. Graphite's weak inter-layer Van der Waals forces make it soft enough to write with and its delocalised electrons make it conductive — ideal for pencils and electrodes. Diamond's all-directional covalent network makes it the hardest natural substance — ideal for cutting tools. Aluminium's metallic bonding makes it malleable and conductive — ideal for sufurias and construction. Water's hydrogen bonds give it a high boiling point and make it a universal solvent — essential for all life and cooking in Kenya.",
      "explained": "The three white solids in the anchoring phenomenon behave so differently because they have fundamentally different bond types and structures: NaCl has an ionic lattice (dissolves in water, conducts when dissolved), SiO₂ has a giant covalent network (does not dissolve, very hard, does not conduct), and graphite has a giant covalent layered structure with delocalised electrons (conducts electricity like a metal, soft enough to mark paper). Every visible, dramatic difference observed on the demonstration bench — dissolving, lighting up the bulb, resisting scratching — is caused entirely by the type of chemical bond holding the atoms together."
    }
