        "teacherMoves": "Introduce the presentation protocol clearly: 'Each group has exactly 4 minutes. You must tell us: (1) the name and formula of your compound, (2) the bond type and how your model shows it, (3) the resultant structure, and (4) at least two physical properties your model helps explain. You must connect your explanation back to Lesson 1 — why did your substance behave the way it did on the demonstration bench?' Display a 4-minute countdown timer. As each group presents, stand to the side — do NOT interrupt unless a factual error is made. If a factual error occurs, pause and say: 'That's interesting — class, do we agree with that? What did our evidence from Lesson [X] show us? WAIT 10 seconds.' After each presentation, give the audience 60 seconds to write their Glow/Grow sticky note. Cold-call one audience member for their Glow and one for their Grow: 'Achieng, what is your Glow for the NaCl group?' and 'Kamau, what is your Grow?' Ensure all four models are presented before moving to the Explain phase. Manage time strictly — give a 30-second warning.",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Strategy: 'Gallery Presentation with Structured Peer Feedback (Glow and Grow)' — presenting a physical 3-D model requires students to translate abstract chemical knowledge into a concrete, observable artefact. Peer observation using the structured observation sheet requires active listening and cross-group comparison, reinforcing that all four compounds can be explained by the same underlying framework (bond type → structure → properties).",
        "formativeAssessment": "Teacher checks Model Observation Sheets for completeness — all four rows should be filled. Key indicators: (1) Does the student correctly identify the bond type for each compound? (2) Does the 'property explained' column match the bond type? (3) Are Glow/Grow sticky notes substantive (e.g., 'Your model shows the layered structure of graphite clearly — Glow') rather than vague ('Good job')? Teacher collects one group's observation sheets at random to review after class."
