        "teacherMoves": "Stand at the DQB. Say: 'This board has been with us since Lesson 1. Every question on it was asked by someone in this room because they were genuinely puzzled. Let us see how far we have come.' Hand green and orange sticky dot stickers to students. Call on individual students by name to approach the board: 'Fatuma, please read the card in the top-left corner and tell us — green or orange? And why?' After each placement, ask the class: 'Agree? Thumbs up if yes, thumbs down if you think it should be different.' WAIT 5 seconds for the vote. If there is disagreement, ask one student from each side to give their reasoning (30 seconds each). After all cards are categorised, point to three prominent RESOLVED questions and celebrate: 'Look — we resolved this one in Lesson 2, this one in Lesson 5, and this one today. That is real science.' Finally, read the driving question aloud slowly: 'How do the chemical bonds between atoms determine the properties and uses of the substances we encounter every day in Kenya?' Ask: 'Hands up — who feels they can now answer this question?' Then say: 'Good. In the next 8 minutes, you will prove it in writing.'",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Strategy: 'DQB Closure Review with Consensus Voting' — revisiting the DQB at unit end makes intellectual progress visible and public. The colour-coding (green = resolved, orange = open) normalises the idea that science always leaves some questions open, while celebrating the genuine conceptual growth achieved. Consensus voting builds shared ownership of the class's collective knowledge.",
        "formativeAssessment": "Teacher observes the quality of student justifications when placing stickers. Key indicator: Can the student cite a specific lesson, activity, or piece of evidence when claiming a question is resolved? Red flag: a student places a green sticker but says only 'we learned about it' without citing specific evidence. Teacher also notes which questions receive orange stickers — these represent genuine gaps that may need follow-up in Sub-Strand 1.5 (Periodicity) or future units."
