        "learnerExperience": "Students spend the final 8 minutes in individual silent writing, composing their Final Explanation in their science notebooks. The prompt is displayed on the board: 'Using at least three specific pieces of evidence from our 8 lessons, explain how the chemical bonds between atoms determine the properties and uses of at least TWO of the following substances you encounter every day in Kenya: table salt (NaCl), sand (SiO₂), graphite (pencil), diamond, aluminium (sufuria), or water (chai). Your explanation must include: the bond type, the resultant structure, at least two physical properties caused by that structure, and one specific Kenyan use.' Students submit this written reflection as they leave — it is the unit's culminating assessment artefact.",
        "teacherMoves": "Display the writing prompt on the board (written in advance on a manila card or projected). Say: 'This is your moment. Eight lessons of evidence. Eight lessons of thinking. Eight lessons of models, experiments, and discussions — all to answer ONE question. You have 8 minutes. Write in complete sentences. Use the evidence — do not just list facts. I will collect your notebooks as you leave.' Set a visible 8-minute countdown timer. Circulate silently for the first 2 minutes — do NOT speak, model that this is serious thinking time. After 2 minutes, crouch beside any student who has written fewer than two sentences and whisper: 'Start with NaCl — what type of bond does it have? Now tell me WHY that bond makes it dissolve in water.' In the final 60 seconds, say: 'One minute — make sure you have named at least two substances, two bond types, and one Kenyan use each.' When time is up: 'Pens down. Please bring your notebook to the front as you leave. Asanteni sana — you have done real chemistry this term.'",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Strategy: 'Individual Final Explanation Writing (Evidence-Based Argument)' — this phase requires each student to independently synthesise all 8 lessons into a coherent, evidence-backed scientific explanation. Writing-to-learn research shows that the act of composing an explanation in one's own words deepens and consolidates conceptual understanding more than any other single activity. Requiring specific evidence citations (lesson activities, observations, model features) prevents superficial recall and demands genuine sensemaking.",
