      "prompt": "Describe how ionic bonds form, using sodium chloride (NaCl) as your main example. Explain what a giant ionic lattice is and how this structure accounts for at least THREE physical properties of ionic compounds that were observed or tested during the unit: solubility in water, electrical conductivity, and high melting point. In your answer, refer specifically to the conductivity test and water test performed during the anchoring phenomenon, and explain — at the particle level — why the salt solution conducted electricity while dry salt or the sand–water mixture did not. You may also refer to other ionic compounds relevant to Kenyan daily life.",
      "exemplar": "Ionic bonds form when one atom transfers one or more electrons to another atom, producing positively charged cations and negatively charged anions. In sodium chloride, a sodium atom (2,8,1) transfers its single valence electron to a chlorine atom (2,8,7), forming Na⁺ (2,8) and Cl⁻ (2,8,8). The strong electrostatic attraction between these oppositely charged ions is the ionic bond. Millions of these ion pairs arrange themselves into a regular, three-dimensional giant ionic lattice — a repeating pattern where every Na⁺ ion is surrounded by six Cl⁻ ions and vice versa. This highly ordered, strongly bonded structure explains all three of the properties we tested in class.\n\nFirst, high melting point: the lattice requires a very large amount of energy to break because every ion is held by multiple strong electrostatic attractions simultaneously. This is why salts used in industrial processes in Kenya, such as in food preservation in Mombasa's fishing industry, remain solid at temperatures well above 100 °C. Second, solubility: when NaCl is added to water, the polar water molecules are attracted to the surface ions, pulling them away one by one and surrounding them (hydration). This is exactly what students observed — the salt 'disappeared' into the water. Sand (SiO₂) did not dissolve because it has no ions; its strong covalent bonds cannot be broken by water molecules. Third, electrical conductivity: dry NaCl does not conduct electricity because the ions are locked in fixed positions in the lattice and cannot move. However, when dissolved in water, the ions become free to move through the solution and carry charge — which is precisely why the bulb lit up when the electrodes were placed in the salt solution during the conductivity test, but remained dark for the sand–water mixture."
