      "exemplar": "In covalent bonding, atoms achieve a full valence shell not by transferring electrons but by sharing them. Each shared pair of electrons is attracted simultaneously by the nuclei of both bonding atoms, creating a covalent bond. For example, two chlorine atoms each contribute one electron to form a shared pair (a single covalent bond, Cl–Cl), and both atoms achieve an octet. This is fundamentally different from ionic bonding, where electrons are fully transferred and ions of opposite charge are produced. A dative covalent bond (also called a coordinate bond) is a special case where one atom donates both electrons of the shared pair. A clear example is the ammonium ion (NH₄⁺): when ammonia (NH₃) reacts with a hydrogen ion (H⁺), the nitrogen atom's lone pair is donated to form a fourth N–H bond — because H⁺ has no electrons to contribute. Once formed, this dative bond is identical in strength to the other three N–H bonds.\n\nSimple molecular covalent substances (like water, H₂O, or carbon dioxide, CO₂) have strong covalent bonds within each molecule but only weak intermolecular forces between molecules. These weak forces require little energy to overcome, so simple molecular substances have low melting and boiling points and are often liquids or gases at room temperature. Giant covalent (atomic) structures, such as silicon dioxide (the sand from Kenyan riverbanks), have covalent bonds extending throughout the entire lattice — every atom is bonded to several others — meaning enormous energy is needed to separate them. This is why sand has an extremely high melting point and does not dissolve in water.\n\nHydrogen bonds form between molecules where hydrogen is bonded to a highly electronegative atom (F, O, or N), creating a partial positive charge on H that is attracted to a lone pair on a neighbouring electronegative atom. In water, each molecule can form up to four hydrogen bonds with its neighbours, making water far more cohesive than expected for its small molecular size. This is why the water in a sufuria of chai takes much longer to boil than students might expect — the many hydrogen bonds must all be overcome before molecules can escape into the gas phase. Van der Waals (London dispersion) forces are even weaker, arising from temporary dipoles in all molecules; they increase with molecular size and explain why larger molecules such as the long-chain hydrocarbons in kerosene (used in Kenyan jiko-type stoves) have higher boiling points than smaller molecules like methane."
