      "exemplar": "Diamond and graphite are both made entirely of carbon atoms, yet they have almost opposite properties — a fact that astonished students during the anchoring phenomenon when the teacher showed that a fingernail scratches graphite easily but a diamond-tipped drill bit can cut through almost anything. The explanation lies entirely in how the carbon atoms are bonded. In diamond, each carbon atom forms four strong covalent bonds arranged tetrahedrally to four neighbouring carbon atoms, creating a rigid, three-dimensional giant covalent lattice with no free electrons and no weak planes. This makes diamond the hardest naturally occurring substance — no electrons are free to carry charge, so diamond does not conduct electricity. In graphite, each carbon atom forms only three covalent bonds to three neighbours in flat, hexagonal layers. The fourth valence electron from each carbon atom is delocalised across the entire layer, forming a 'sea' of mobile electrons above and below each sheet. The layers themselves are held together only by weak Van der Waals forces, which means they slide past each other easily — this is why graphite feels slippery and why it marks paper in a school pencil. The delocalised electrons allow graphite to conduct electricity, which is exactly why the bulb lit up when the graphite rod was placed in the circuit during the anchoring phenomenon.\n\nMetallic bonding is the electrostatic attraction between a lattice of positive metal ions (cations) and a surrounding 'sea' of delocalised electrons that have been released from each metal atom's valence shell. Consider the aluminium sufuria found in nearly every Kenyan kitchen: each aluminium atom releases three valence electrons into the delocalised sea, leaving behind an Al³⁺ ion held in the lattice. Because the delocalised electrons can move freely throughout the entire metallic structure, they carry charge efficiently — explaining why aluminium and copper conduct electricity well, making copper the material of choice for electrical wiring across Kenya. The metallic bond is also non-directional, meaning that when a force is applied — for example, when a blacksmith in Kamuthe hammers iron into a jembe — the layers of cations can slide past each other while still remaining attracted to the electron sea. This accounts for malleability (ability to be beaten into sheets) and ductility (ability to be drawn into wires) — properties that would be impossible in an ionic lattice, where sliding layers would bring like charges together and cause the structure to shatter."
