      "prompt": "Now bring everything together to answer the unit's Driving Question in full: 'How do the chemical bonds between atoms determine the properties and uses of the substances we encounter every day in Kenya?' Choose at least THREE different substances from the anchoring phenomenon or from Kenyan daily life that represent at least THREE different bond types (e.g., ionic, metallic, giant covalent, simple covalent, or substances involving intermolecular forces). For each substance, name the bond type, describe one key property it produces, and explain one specific use in a Kenyan context that directly depends on that property. Reflect on how your understanding has changed from Lesson 1 (when you first saw the three solids on the bench) to now.",
      "exemplar": "The Driving Question of this unit — how chemical bonds determine the properties and uses of everyday Kenyan substances — can now be answered with confidence using the evidence and models built across all eight lessons. The key insight is this: the type of bond holding atoms together at the invisible, atomic level directly and predictably causes the visible, measurable properties that determine how a substance can be used in the real world.\n\nFirst, table salt (NaCl) is held together by ionic bonds in a giant lattice. This structure gives it a high melting point (so it remains solid in a hot Kenyan kitchen), solubility in water (so it dissolves into food and into body fluids to regulate nerve function), and the ability to conduct electricity when dissolved (making electrolyte solutions medically useful). Kenyan coastal communities have harvested salt from Malindi and the Tana Delta for generations — a use made possible entirely by salt's ionic bonding and the resulting solubility.\n\nSecond, aluminium — used in sufurias, roofing sheets, and electrical wiring across Kenya — is held together by metallic bonds. The delocalised electron sea makes it an excellent conductor of heat (essential for cooking ugali evenly) and electricity (essential for rural electrification projects), while the non-directional nature of the metallic bond makes it malleable enough to be pressed into cookware shapes. Third, graphite in pencils is a giant covalent structure with delocalised electrons between its carbon layers; weak Van der Waals forces between its layers allow them to slide onto paper, and its conductivity makes it useful in electrodes. Fourth, water — central to Kenyan life from the Mara River to Lake Victoria — owes its unusually high boiling point, surface tension, and ability to dissolve ionic substances entirely to its hydrogen bonds and polar covalent O–H bonds. Without these properties, chai could not be brewed and crops could not be irrigated efficiently.\n\nAt the start of this unit, the three solids on the bench appeared mysterious. Now the 'mystery' is fully explained: atoms bond to achieve stability, the mechanism they use (transfer, sharing, or delocalisation of electrons) produces a specific structure, and that structure determines every property we can observe and every use we assign to a material. The invisible world of electrons has made itself visible — in every sufuria, every pencil mark, and every grain of salt on a plate of ugali."
